	<div id="comment_top_64356612" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64356612" name="comment_link_64356612" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274262&amp;cid=64356612" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64356612)" >Ironically the GOP in Texas is anti green energy</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64356612" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64356612); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~UnknowingFool">UnknowingFool</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~UnknowingFool">( 672806 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64356612">		
		on Saturday March 30, 2024 @01:11PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274262&amp;cid=64356612">#64356612</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64356612">A few years ago (2022) when the entire state suffered a week of power blackouts due to extreme cold, the GOP in control of the state was quick to blame wind energy outages. That was despite the fact that gas plants failed for the same reason: Most of the industry had not been winterized for prolong sub-freezing conditions. Ten years (2012) earlier Texas narrowly avoided a long outage. An official report recommended that Texas plants winterize operations to avoid future problems. Those recommendations were not implemented. But green energy was to blame according to the GOP.</div>
	</div>

